Introduction¶

Tunisair serves 54 destinations in scheduled flights between Africa, Europe and the Middle East.
The bulk of Tunisair's business is concentrated in Europe, particularly in France, with 9 routes (Paris Orly, Marseille, Nantes, etc.) compared with 5 in Italy and Germany (respectively Rome, Milan Venice and Frankfurt, Hamburg, Berlin). ..).
The rest of the 32 European destinations are spread over the rest of the mainland countries such as Switzerland, London, Belgium, etc.
Although belonging to the African continent, Tunisair serves only 14 African destinations for the majority concentrated on the north and west of Africa (Algiers, Casa, Tripoli, Benghazi, Oran, Dakar, Bamako, etc.).
This choice was justified by socio-economic factors relating to the rest of the continent (low income, lack of appropriate infrastructure, political instability, etc.).
However, the situation has changed and the indicators of the various components of the environment are improving, albeit slowly, but still continuing.
Note in this regard, that in its 2012 recovery plan, the company plans the closure of unprofitable lines and the development of a set of services on the African continent benefiting from the growth of passenger and cargo traffic on the latter
Like any company, Tunisair airline has in its assets, some that can be translated into competitive advantages but also handicaps that could negatively affect its development prospects in general and the African continent in particular.
An internal diagnosis is able to list those elements that, faced with opportunities and threats, make it possible to set up more effective strategic actions.

First step : Business understandings¶

Business Objectives :

Suggest improvements, Tunisair could make to their fleet in order to attain the international standard profile.
Help Tunisair to be among the best airlines in Africa

Data Science Goals :

Categorize aircrafts models
Determine the international standard profile of aircrafts
Study Tunisair's fleet and international airlines fleets 's characteristics

Second step : Data understandings¶

Scraping from

import pandas as pd
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup

fname = r"C:\Users\Sedki\Desktop\Etude de la flotte Tunisair\BangkokAirways.html"
HtmlFile = open(fname, 'r', encoding='utf-8')
source_code = HtmlFile.read()
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
soup = BeautifulSoup(source_code, 'html.parser')

table = soup.find('tbody')
rows = table.find_all('tr')

Airline = []
AircraftWithSeatmap = []
SeatPitch = []
SeatWidth = []
VideoType = []
LaptopPower = []
PowerType = []
WiFi = []
SeatType = []
rows
for tr in rows:
    cols = tr.find_all('td')
   
    AircraftWithSeatmap.append(cols[1].text.strip())
    SeatPitch.append(cols[2].text.strip())
    SeatWidth.append(cols[3].text.strip())
    VideoType.append(cols[4].text.strip())
    
    
    WiFi.append(cols[7].text.strip())
   
    

PremiumEconomyClass = pd.DataFrame(data={'Reg':AircraftWithSeatmap,
                        'AircraftType':SeatPitch,'config':SeatWidth,'delivered':VideoType,
                        'Age':WiFi
                         })

PremiumEconomyClass=PremiumEconomyClass[['Reg', 'AircraftType', 'config','delivered',
                                        'Age']]

PremiumEconomyClass.head(10)

from pandas.plotting import parallel_coordinates

#clusterer = KMeans(n_clusters=2, random_state=10)
x = delta.loc[:,'Seat Width (First Class)':'Seat Width (Eco Comfort)']
x.columns=[ 'Seat Width (First Class)','Seat Pitch (First Class)','Seats (First Class)','Seat Width (Business)',
           'Seat Pitch (Business)','Seats (Business)','Seat Width (Eco Comfort)']
delta['cluster']=cluster_labels
y=delta["cluster"]

X_norm = (x - x.min())/(x.max() - x.min())
# Select features to include in the plot
plot_feat = ['Seat Width (First Class)','Seat Pitch (First Class)','Seats (First Class)','Seat Width (Business)',
           'Seat Pitch (Business)','Seats (Business)','Seat Width (Eco Comfort)']
# Concat classes with the normalized data
data_norm = pd.concat([X_norm[plot_feat], y], axis=1)
plt.figure(figsize=(15,8))
# Perform parallel coordinate plot
parallel_coordinates(data_norm, 'cluster',color=['m','g','y'])
plt.show()

df = pd.DataFrame({
'cl': ["0","1","2"],
'class business': [cl0['Seat Width (Business)'].median(),cl1['Seat Width (Business)'].median(),cl2['Seat Width (Business)'].median()],
'class economy': [cl0['Seat Width (Economy)'].median(),cl1['Seat Width (Economy)'].median(),cl2['Seat Width (Economy)'].median()],
'first class': [cl0['Seat Width (First Class)'].median(),cl1['Seat Width (First Class)'].median(),
                cl2['Seat Width (First Class)'].median()],
'class eco comfort': [cl0['Seat Width (Eco Comfort)'].median(),cl1['Seat Width (Eco Comfort)'].median(),cl2['Seat Width (Eco Comfort)'].median() ]

})

# Set data

 
# ------- PART 1: Define a function that do a plot for one line of the dataset!
 
def make_spider( row, title, color):
    
    categories=list(df)[1:]
    N = len(categories)
 
    # What will be the angle of each axis in the plot? (we divide the plot / number of variable)
    angles = [n / float(N) * 2 * pi for n in range(N)]
    angles += angles[:1]
 
# Initialise the spider plot
    ax = plt.subplot(2,2,row+1, polar=True, )
 
# If you want the first axis to be on top:
    ax.set_theta_offset(pi / 2)
    ax.set_theta_direction(-1)
 
# Draw one axe per variable + add labels labels yet
    plt.xticks(angles[:-1], categories, color='grey', size=8)
 
# Draw ylabels
    ax.set_rlabel_position(0)
    plt.yticks([10,20,30], ["10","20","30"], color="grey", size=8)
    plt.ylim(0,30)
 
# Ind1
    values=df.loc[row].drop('cl').values.flatten().tolist()
    values += values[:1]
    ax.plot(angles, values, color=color, linewidth=2, linestyle='solid')
    ax.fill(angles, values, color=color, alpha=0.4)

 
# Add a title
    plt.title(title, size=11, color=color, y=1.1)
 
# ------- PART 2: Apply to all individuals
# initialize the figure
my_dpi=96
plt.figure(figsize=(1000/my_dpi, 1000/my_dpi), dpi=my_dpi)
 
# Create a color palette:
my_palette = plt.cm.get_cmap("Set2", len(df.index))
 
# Loop to plot
for row in range(0, len(df.index)):
    make_spider( row=row, title='group '+str(df['cl'][row]), color=my_palette(row))

Conlusion and perspective:¶

Tunisair's fleet's Age:

The fleet's age of Tunisair is very high compared to the average age of the other companies all around the world This is a weak point for Tunisair ,which can be an obstacle for this company to reach its goal and be among the best airlines in Africa

Tunisair's fleet's Price:

The average cost of Tunisair fleet is the lowest compared to MAROC AIRCRAFTS and EGYPT AIRCRAFTS (Tunisair's competitor in the africain market) We notice that the total price cost of the fleet for each airline depends on its size. The cost of Tunisair fleet is among the least expensive internationally that is due to its small size Tunisair's aircrafts average to a quiet similar cost to their international rivals, a reasonable deduction would be that the afore mentionned aircrafts are conform with the standard profile. Even though Tunisair follows a very average and standard protocol in terms of their aircrafts, keeping them after their best usage period is harmful for their market share on both the long and the short term run. Proposed Solution : rejuvenation of Tunisair's fleet

Tunisair's fleet's Size:

The current Tunisair's fleet consists on 30 aircrafts

Tunisair's fleet size is modest compared to other fleets.

So to dominate African market Tunisair must target customers with their prefered Aircraft which is in this cas Boeing B737-800[2] which belongs to the same aircrafts standard profile as Tunisair's fleet , it means it's affordable by this company and this can be considered as a strenght for Tunisair.
